data: General of Outworld's Tarkatan warriors, under Shao Kahn's rule.
Loyal ninja assassin for the Lin Kuei who apprehensively undergoes automation into a cybernetic warrior.
Fighter composed of the souls of multiple dead warriors; also possesses the power of psychokinesis.
Captain of the Deacon City Police Department, and Sonya's longtime partner.
Famous actor struggling to maintain his fame after a string of controversies. Fights alongside Earth's defenders in Season 2.
Notorious thug and head of the Black Dragon crime cartel.
Blind swordsman possessing the power of telekinesis.
Former King of Edenia, father of Kitana and husband of Queen Sindel.

Former princess of Edenia, daughter of King Jerrod and Queen Sindel; raised as an assassin by Emperor Shao Kahn. She entered the tournament alongside Shang Tsung's forces but later turned against them.
Lieutenant of the Deacon City Police Department alongside Jax and Sonya. Fights alongside Earth's defenders in Season 2.
Friend of Liu Kang and fellow Shaolin monk. Fights alongside Earth's defenders in Season 2.
A violent and sociopathic former Shaolin monk turned vigilante and former friend of Kung Lao. He joins the tournament fighting alongside Shang Tsung.
A half-Edenian, half-Tarkatan clone of Kitana, trained as Kahn's loyal assassin.
A sorcerer allied to Shang Tsung on the side of the Netherrealm.
The former queen of Edenia; wife of King Jerrod and mother of Princess Kitana.
God of Thunder and Protector of Earthrealm. Leads Earth's warriors in the defense against Shang Tsung's forces.

General of the Japanese Shirai Ryu ninja clan, who are rivals of the Lin Kuei. Due to the fear of inheriting his father's unhealthy sense of hatred, he agreed to a truce to end the war started by Sub-Zero. He joined fighting for alongside Shang Tsung.
Loyal ninja assassin for the Lin Kuei who willingly undergoes automation into a cybernetic warrior.
Nefarious sorcerer serving Shao Kahn. In season two, hosts the Mortal Kombat tournament, leading his warriors against those of Earthrealm.
Emperor of Outworld; adoptive father to Kitana and Mileena.
Lieutenant in the Deacon City police department and Jax's partner.
Assassin for the Lin Kuei clan, who are rivals of the Shirai Ryu. He tires of the war between the clans and therefore calls a truce. Fights alongside Earth's defenders in Season 2.
Lin Kuei assassin who dons the costume and identity of his deceased older brother, Bi-Han. Described as a "warlord advisor."

table-0917-949.caption: April 4 event
data: A metal building and a carport were destroyed and many trees were knocked down.
A barn was damaged and nine chicken houses were heavily damaged. A tractor trailer was also flipped.
Severe damage on a chicken farm with a trailer and four chicken houses destroyed, with hundreds of chicken killed. Two people were injured on the farm.
Many trees were snapped or knocked down, some falling on a house with significant damage and a large storage building which was destroyed.
Damage to trees, power poles and power lines.
Several houses sustained minor roof damage.
Numerous houses, barns, outbuildings and a gas station were damaged.
Two barns were destroyed and trees were snapped or uprooted.
A house was heavily damaged and several others sustained minor damage. Numerous farm buildings and sheds were destroyed and two mobile homes were flipped. One person was injured.
A metal farm building was damaged and two vehicles were heavily damaged. Several trees were snapped.
Severe damage at a mobile home park where three people were injured.
A large industrial factory was heavily damaged, where seven people were injured. Two barns were flattened and two houses were also damaged.
Several houses were damaged, including a house that lost its roof and a mobile home that was removed from its foundation. Trees were also snapped.
Three large grain bins were thrown on a mining company site with damage to other buildings. Two mobile homes were also damaged.
A house and a barn sustained roof damage and many trees were uprooted or snapped.
A large barn was heavily damaged and trees were snapped by this brief tornado.
Brief tornado destroyed a shed and damaged a barn and a house.
Several barns and outbuildings were damaged and many trees were snapped or knocked down.
Brief tornado destroyed a mobile home and knocked down about 100 trees.
Several businesses were damaged in town, and many trees were knocked down. Some of the trees landed on houses and vehicles with damage to them.
Dozens of trees were snapped and uprooted.
Very brief tornado with damage limited to a few trees.
A few houses were damaged, a building lost its roof and some trees were knocked down.
Numerous houses were damaged and many trees were snapped or uprooted.
A hunting camp was heavily damaged. Severe damage to trees and power poles.
Numerous houses were heavily damaged or destroyed and the parish's water system was heavily impacted by a long track, large wedge tornado. One person was injured.
One home sustained major roof damage, and there was minor roof damage to two mobile homes. Several large trees were completely uprooted.
One house sustained roof damage and numerous trees were snapped.
A carport was lifted, significantly damaging a house.
A mobile home was damaged and numerous trees were knocked down.
Many pine trees were snapped and two outbuildings were destroyed.
Large but relatively weak tornado with widespread tree damage, a few of the trees landed on houses.
Many houses were damaged along with a church, a gas station and a fire station. Extensive tree damage along the path.
A house lost its roof and numerous trees were uprooted.
Long track tornado with widespread damage. Possibly one or multiple tornadoes.
Brief tornado damaged two houses and two commercial buildings.
Hundreds of trees were knocked down, a few landing on houses. Tornado embedded in larger microburst.
A chicken house and an outbuilding were destroyed and trees were snapped.

data: Anó ang pangalan ninyo/nila*? (plural or polite) [ɐˈno aŋ pɐˈŋaːlan nɪnˈjo] , Anó ang pangalan mo? (singular) [ɐˈno aŋ pɐˈŋaːlan mo]

Depending on the nature of the verb, either pakí- [pɐˈki] or makí- [mɐˈki] is attached as a prefix to a verb. ngâ [ŋaʔ] is optionally added after the verb to increase politeness. (e.g. Pakipasa ngâ ang tinapay. ("Can you pass the bread, please?"))
iyan [ʔiˈjan] , When pointing to something at greater distances: iyun [ʔiˈjʊn] or iyon [ʔiˈjon]
hindî [hɪnˈdɛʔ] , often shortened to dî [dɛʔ] hindî pô (formal/polite form)
hindî ko álam [hɪnˈdɛʔ ko aːlam] Very informal: ewan [ʔɛˈʊɑn] , archaic aywan [ɑjˈʊɑn] (closest English equivalent: colloquial dismissive 'Whatever')
pasensya pô (literally from the word "patience") or paumanhin po [pɐˈsɛːnʃa poʔ] patawad po [pɐtaːwad poʔ] (literally—"asking your forgiveness")
